AustinBikeShare

Objective:

  1. How much do weather and seasonality influence the Daily Cumulative Bike Rentals in Austin, Texas per day.
  2. To build a predictive model for Daily Cumulative Bike Rentals in Austin, Texas based on weather and seasonality.

This file contains the data corresponding to each of the bike rental in Austin, Texas.

There are two possible response variables here. 1. Daily cumulative bike rental duration in hours 2. Total Count of bike rentals per day

bikes$start_date = date(bikes$start_time)
bikes2 = bikes %>%
  group_by(start_date) %>%
  summarize(TotDur = sum(duration_minutes),
            TotalCount = n()) %>%
  ungroup()
## `summarise()` ungrouping output (override with `.groups` argument)

Loading the daily weather data and using only the average weather data for analysis because the average is more representative of the daily weather when compared to highs and lows.

weather = read.csv("austin_weather.csv", header = T)
weather$Date = mdy(weather$Date)
req_cols = c("Date","TempAvgF","DewPointAvgF","HumidityAvgPercent","SeaLevelPressureAvgInches","VisibilityAvgMiles","WindAvgMPH","PrecipitationSumInches","Events")
weather = weather[req_cols]

bikes2 = bikes2 %>%
  left_join(weather, by = c("start_date"="Date"))

Data Cleaning

  1. Precipitation has trace amounts noted as T. This indicates the amount of precipitation which cannot be measured (usually lower than 0.01 inches). So I replaced it with 0.005 inches. (since I know that it is higher than 0)
  2. Converting the binary columns to factors.
  3. Creating Month and Weekday from start date
  4. Renaming the columns to shorter names for ease of use.
  5. Splitting the dataset into two: One having data from 2014-2016 which is used to build the model and 2017s data which will be used for checking predictions.
bikes2$Precipitation = as.numeric(bikes2$PrecipitationSumInches)
## Warning: NAs introduced by coercion
bikes2 <- bikes2 %>%
  mutate(AdverseEvent = if_else(str_length(Events)>1,1,0)) %>%
  select(-Events) %>%
  replace(is.na(.), 0.005) %>%
  select(-PrecipitationSumInches)

bikes2$AdverseEvent = as.factor(bikes2$AdverseEvent)

bikes2$DayOfWeek = wday(bikes2$start_date,week_start = getOption("lubridate.week.start", 1))

bikes2 <- bikes2 %>%
  mutate(Weekday = if_else(DayOfWeek <=4, 1,0)) %>%
  select(-DayOfWeek)

bikes2$Weekday = as.factor(bikes2$Weekday)
bikes2$Month = month(bikes2$start_date)

newcolnames = c("start_date","TotDur","TotCnt","Temp","DewPt","Humid",
                "Pressure","Visib","WindSpd","Precip","AdvEvent","Weekday","Month")
colnames(bikes2) = newcolnames

bikes1416 <- bikes2 %>%
  filter(year(start_date) >=2014 & year(start_date)<=2016)

bikes17 <- bikes2 %>%
  filter(year(start_date) ==2017)

Creating the final dataset for regression i.e., removing any unnecessary columns and also creating the train/test sets

reg_data = bikes1416 %>% select(-c(start_date,TotCnt))
#Creating test and train 
K = 10
N = nrow(reg_data)
nTest = N*K/100
KI = c(seq(1,N,1+round(nTest)),N) # gives a vector of indices for test sets
set.seed(1) #setting seed to the the same random values every time in the next line
reg_data = reg_data[sample(N),] # randomizes the rows

ind = c(KI[1]:KI[2])
test = reg_data[ind,]
train = reg_data[!(c(1:N) %in% ind),]

Modeling:

This is base model with all the variables used as-is. For the purpose of Cross-Validation, we randomly converted the dataset into 10 train (90%) and test (10%) sets and the model outputs shown in the report corresponds to the first train set.

1. Scale-Location Plot: shows a slight curvature 2. Normal QQ plot: Shows highly skewed points. 3. Leverage Plot: Quite a lot of points with standardized residuals over 4.

Since the assumptions of MLR do not hold here we can perform transformations to fix those issues.

Transformation of Variables

I will use the boxcox method for transformation of non-categorical variables.

boxcox = powerTransform(
        cbind(TotDur, Temp, DewPt, Humid, Pressure, Visib, WindSpd) ~ -1, data = train)

I will create a new dataframe with transformed variables and also use a few interactions based on general knowledge.

  1. Month and Temperature
  2. Temperature and Dew
  3. Temperature and Humidity
  4. Visibility and Humidity
  5. Wind and Pressure
#Transforming the variables
ttrain = NULL
ttrain$tTotDur = train$TotDur^0.15
ttrain$Weekday = train$Weekday
ttrain$sinMonth = sin(2*pi*train$Month/12)
ttrain$cosMonth = cos(2*pi*train$Month/12)
ttrain$Temp = train$Temp
ttrain$DewPt = train$DewPt
ttrain$tHumid = train$Humid^0.5
ttrain$tPressure = train$Pressure^-6.35
ttrain$tVisib = train$Visib^6.66
ttrain$tWindSpd = train$WindSpd^0.5
ttrain$AdvEvent = train$AdvEvent
ttrain = as.data.frame(ttrain)
ttrain$Weekday = as.factor(ttrain$Weekday)
ttrain$AdvEvent = as.factor(ttrain$AdvEvent)

#interactions
ttrain$sinM_Temp = ttrain$sinMonth*ttrain$Temp
ttrain$cosM_Temp = ttrain$cosMonth*ttrain$Temp
ttrain$Temp_Dew = ttrain$Temp*ttrain$DewPt
ttrain$Temp_tHumid = ttrain$Temp*ttrain$tHumid
ttrain$tVisib_tHumid = ttrain$tVisib*ttrain$tHumid
ttrain$tWind_tPressure = ttrain$tWindSpd*ttrain$tPressure

The transformed. model is a lot better than the base model with a much higher adjusted R-squared value with a few significant interactions. But there is some redundant information which can be removed using data driven Model Selection

backBIC <- step(tmodel1, direction="backward", data=ttrain, k = log(nrow(ttrain)))
backAIC <- step(tmodel1, direction="backward", data=ttrain)

THe model obtained from running Backward Elimination using BIC is as follows

  1. Weekday
  2. sinM_Temp
  3. cosM_Temp
  4. sinMonth
  5. cosMonth
  6. DewPt
  7. tHumid
  8. tWindSpd
  9. AdvEvent
  10. tVisib_tHumid

Seven of these are the actual variables and three are interactions.

The variables obtained from using Backward Elimination with AIC is as follows

  1. tPressure
  2. tVisib
  3. AdvEvent
  4. tVisib_tHumid
  5. Temp_Dew
  6. Temp_tHumid
  7. DewPt
  8. sinMonth
  9. tWindSpd
  10. cosM_Temp
  11. cosMonth
  12. sinM_Temp
  13. tHumid
  14. Weekday

Model obtained with Backward Elimination using AIC has the smallest RMSE value which also has the highest average adjusted R-squared value.

Lets look at the diagnostics of the Model obtained from Backward Elimination with AIC to check the validity of the model.

modelaic <- lm(tTotDur ~ Weekday + sinM_Temp + cosM_Temp + sinMonth + cosMonth +
                 DewPt + tHumid + tPressure + tVisib + tWindSpd + AdvEvent +
                 tVisib_tHumid + Temp_tHumid + Temp_Dew,
               data = ttrain)
StanRes = rstandard(modelaic)
par(mfrow = c(4,4))
for(i in 1:(ncol(ttrain)-1)){
  plot(ttrain[,i+1],StanRes, xlab = colnames(ttrain)[i+1])
}

There are no obvious patterns in each of the residuals plots so we can say that nothing is wrong with the model so far.

par(mfrow = c(4,4))
for(i in 1:(ncol(ttrain)-1)){
  if(!is.factor(ttrain[,i+1])){
    mmp(modelaic, ttrain[,i+1], xlab = colnames(ttrain)[i+1])
  }else{
    mmp(modelaic, as.numeric(ttrain[,i+1]), xlab = colnames(ttrain)[i+1])
  }
}

The marginal model plots shows the comparison of the linear model and the non-parametric model. Since both of them are very close to each other we can conclude that linearity assumption holds. (the adverse event plot looks weird, this may be due to the fact that this variable is a categorical variable.)

par(mfrow = c(2,2))
plot(modelaic)

Normal QQ plot: Mostly normal with heavy tails. Leverage Plot: No Influential Points. No bad leverage points.
